Wilde packed his bags and moved to London, where he began

00:07:41.421 --> 00:07:45.761
publishing poems and short stories for literary magazines.

00:07:46.261 --> 00:07:50.841
He was the Victorian equivalent of a newspaper columnist, really.

00:07:51.951 --> 00:07:57.061
Although he made a decent amount of money from this, it was to be a lecture

00:07:57.061 --> 00:08:02.641
tour of the United States that was the real money-maker for the young Wilde.

00:08:03.811 --> 00:08:12.431
In 1882, aged 27, he embarked on a year-long tour of America where he lectured on

00:08:12.571 --> 00:08:18.091
Aestheticism, this new movement that was taking much of the literary world by storm.

00:08:19.541 --> 00:08:25.581
He was very well aware of his own talents, and he was certainly not a modest man.

00:08:26.471 --> 00:08:33.371
You may be aware of one of his most famous quotes, where he is reported to have said to a

00:08:33.451 --> 00:08:40.671
customs official when he arrived in the US, “I have nothing to declare except my genius”.

00:08:41.690 --> 00:08:45.900
While on tour in the US and after returning home, a rich

00:08:45.900 --> 00:08:49.947
man, he loved the attention and fame that followed him.

00:08:50.635 --> 00:08:54.945
There were reports of him walking down Piccaddily, a famous street

00:08:54.975 --> 00:08:59.665
in London, carrying a lily flower and with his long hair flowing.

